## Example 4 — The Empirical Rule

A normal distribution has a mean of [μ = 186.4] and a standard deviation of [σ = 48.9].

a. What range of values represents the middle 99.7% of the data?
[μ - 3σ to μ + 3σ]
[186.4 - 3(48.9) to 186.4 + 3(48.9)]
[186.4 - 146.7 to 186.4 + 146.7]
[39.7 to 333.1]

b. What percent of data will be greater than 235.3?
[235.3 = 186.4 + 48.9 = μ + σ]
By the empirical rule, about 16% of data lies above [μ + σ] (one standard deviation above the mean).

c. What range of values represents the upper 2.5% of the data?
The upper 2.5% corresponds to values greater than [μ + 2σ] (since about 95% lies within 2 SD).
[186.4 + 2(48.9) = 186.4 + 97.8 = 284.2]
So the upper 2.5% is greater than approximately 284.2.

## Example 5 — Calculate z-Values

Find the z-value for each standard normal distribution.

8. [σ = 9.8, X = 55.4, μ = 68.34]
[z = (55.4 - 68.34) / 9.8 = -12.94 / 9.8 ≈ -1.32]

9. [σ = 11.6, X = 42.80, μ = 68.2]
[z = (42.80 - 68.2) / 11.6 = -25.4 / 11.6 ≈ -2.19]

10. [σ = 11.6, X = 119.2, μ = 112.4]
[z = (119.2 - 112.4) / 11.6 = 6.8 / 11.6 ≈ 0.59]

