## Example 7 — Apply Normal Distribution to Real Data

### Step 1: Testing Scores Problem

Test scores are normally distributed with a mean of [μ = 100] and a standard deviation of [σ = 12.3].

a. What percent of scores are between 70 and 80?
[z for 70: (70 - 100) / 12.3 ≈ -2.44]
[z for 80: (80 - 100) / 12.3 ≈ -1.63]
Use the z-table to find the area between these z-values.

b. What percent of scores are over 115?
[z for 115: (115 - 100) / 12.3 ≈ 1.22]
Area to the right of [z = 1.22] from the z-table.

c. If 75 people take the test, how many would you expect to score lower than 75?
First find the area to the left of [z = (75 - 100) / 12.3 ≈ -2.03].
Then multiply 75 by that proportion.

## Mixed Exercises

15. Shawndra studied how far people park from parking blocks. Mean is 8.5 inches, and about 2.5% park more than 11.5 inches. What percentage park less than 5.5 inches?
If the distribution is symmetric and normal, 5.5 inches is the same distance below the mean as 11.5 is above. So about 2.5% also park less than 5.5 inches.

16. Use the normal distribution of data to answer:
a. What is the standard deviation of the data set?
b. What percent of the data will be greater than 60? ![](media/image4.png)

17. Light bulbs: About 2.5% last longer than 6800 hours, and about 16% last longer than 6500 hours. What is the average bulb life?
Use the empirical rule: if 16% last longer than 6500, then 6500 is approximately [μ + σ]. If 2.5% last longer than 6800, then 6800 is approximately [μ + 2σ].
Solving gives approximate values for [μ] and [σ].

18. Roberto takes a 20-question practice college entrance exam daily and records his score. Find the probability distribution.
Each score can range from 0 to 20, and the distribution would show the probability of each possible score.

19. Tree diameters: Mean 11.5 cm, standard deviation 2.5, range 3.6 to 19.8. Monica and Hiroko find the range for the middle 68%. Is either correct?
The middle 68% is within [μ - σ, μ + σ] = [9.0, 14.0]. The actual range 3.6 to 19.8 spans more than 3 standard deviations, so the middle 68% would fall within [9.0, 14.0].

20. Cell phone shipment: Average battery life 8.2 hours with standard deviation 0.7 hour. Eight phones have battery life greater than 9.3 hours. If normally distributed, how many phones are in the shipment?
[9.3 = 8.2 + 1.1 = 8.2 + (1.57)(0.7) ≈ μ + 1.57σ]
From the z-table, about 5.8% of phones exceed this value.
If 8 phones represent 5.8%, then total phones ≈ 8 / 0.058 ≈ 138.

21. Describe the relationship between the z-value, position of an interval of X in the normal distribution, area under the normal curve, and probability of the interval occurring.
The z-value indicates how many standard deviations X is from the mean. The z-value's position determines the area under the normal curve, which equals the probability of X falling in that interval.

